.TH SENTINELBOX 1 "May 2026" "SentinelBox 1.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
sentinelbox \- secure, rootless sandbox for AI-generated code with semantic feedback

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sentinelbox
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \-\- \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sentinelbox
is a high-performance, rootless sandbox designed specifically for executing untrusted code generated by Artificial Intelligence (AI) Agents. It achieves strict isolation utilizing Linux Kernel primitives: PID, Mount, Network, and User namespaces. 

Unlike traditional static containers (e.g., Docker) which return opaque error codes when an action is denied, SentinelBox features a \fIsemantic feedback loop\fR. It intercepts forbidden system calls via seccomp-bpf and the 
.B SECCOMP_RET_USER_NOTIF
feature, passing the context to a dedicated Rust monitor process. This monitor translates the low-level kernel signal into a natural-language explanation, allowing AI agents utilizing the Model Context Protocol (MCP) to understand exactly \fIwhy\fR their code failed and how to repair it.

Filesystem isolation is achieved using \fBpivot_root\fR(2) in conjunction with an \fBOverlayFS\fR mounted over a RAM-backed \fBtmpfs\fR. This ensures that all writes are ephemeral, allowing for near-instantaneous (<20ms) environment resets.

.SH ARCHITECTURE
SentinelBox operates across four logical layers:
.TP
.B 1. Core Isolation Engine (C)
Responsible for setting up Linux Namespaces (\fICLONE_NEWUSER\fR, \fICLONE_NEWPID\fR, etc.), dropping capabilities, configuring the ephemeral OverlayFS, and setting Cgroup v2 limits.
.TP
.B 2. Security Sentinel (Rust)
The \fBsentinelbox-monitor\fR binary. It runs as a detached process, communicating with the core engine via UNIX domain sockets to receive the \fBnotify_fd\fR. It polls for intercepted system calls, evaluates them against the active JSON profile, and logs telemetry to a local SQLite database.
.TP
.B 3. Semantic Translator (MCP Server / TypeScript)
An independent service that reads the SQLite audit database and provides tools (\fBtranslate_error\fR, \fBsuggest_repair\fR) to an upstream AI Agent via the Model Context Protocol.
.TP
.B 4. Telemetry Dashboard (React)
A real-time Web UI that consumes telemetry and security events via WebSockets.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-\-profile=\fINAME\fR
Apply the security constraints defined in
.IR profiles/NAME .json.
Default:
.IR strict .
Built-in profiles include:
.IR strict " (No network, minimal syscalls)",
.IR datascience " (Allows specific data-processing syscalls and relaxed memory)",
.IR web " (Allows network access)".

.TP
.BR \-\-profile\-dir=\fIDIR\fR
Directory holding profile JSON files. Default:
.IR ./profiles .

.TP
.BR \-\-rootfs=\fIPATH\fR
\fBMandatory.\fR The path to the read-only base rootfs used as the OverlayFS
.IR lowerdir .
Typically created by the bundled
.BR setup_rootfs.sh (1) script.

.TP
.BR \-\-monitor=\fIPATH\fR
Path to the
.B sentinelbox-monitor
Rust binary. Default:
.IR ./monitor/target/release/sentinelbox-monitor .

.TP
.BR \-\-cgroup\-parent=\fIPATH\fR
Parent cgroup under which the per-execution cgroup is created.
Default:
.IR /sys/fs/cgroup .
For rootless, unprivileged usage, point this at the user's delegated systemd subtree
(e.g., \fI/sys/fs/cgroup/user.slice/user-1000.slice/user@1000.service\fR). See the \fBsetup_cgroup.sh\fR script.

.TP
.BR \-\-no\-monitor
Disable launching the Rust monitor. In this mode, SentinelBox degrades to a traditional sandbox. Profile rules configured with the
.B NOTIFY
action will automatically degrade to
.B ERRNO=EPERM
as there is no monitor attached to handle the user notification.

.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable verbose, debug-level logging on stderr from the C engine.

.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print built-in help and exit.

.SH PROFILE FORMAT
Security profiles define the exact boundaries of the sandbox. They are authored in JSON:
.TP
.B name
(String) The identifier of the profile.
.TP
.B default_action
(String) The fallback action for any syscall not explicitly listed. Must be one of:
.IR ALLOW " (Permit), "
.IR ERRNO " (Deny with EPERM), "
.IR NOTIFY " (Send to Rust monitor for semantic translation), or "
.IR KILL " (Terminate process instantly)."
.TP
.B syscall_rules
(Array) Explicit rules for specific system calls. Format: \fI{"name": "socket", "action": "NOTIFY", "errno": 1}\fR.
.TP
.B resources
(Object) Cgroup v2 constraints. Includes \fImem_limit_bytes\fR, \fIcpu_max_quota\fR, \fIcpu_max_period\fR, and \fIpids_max\fR.
.TP
.B network
(Object) High-level network toggles (e.g., \fIallow_dns\fR).

.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.TP
.B SENTINELBOX_LOG
Sets the tracing-subscriber log level for the Rust monitor. Valid values: \fIerror\fR, \fIwarn\fR, \fIinfo\fR, \fIdebug\fR, \fItrace\fR. Default is \fIinfo\fR.
.TP
.B SENTINELBOX_DB
Path where the Rust monitor writes the SQLite WAL audit log. Default: \fI./sentinelbox.db\fR.
.TP
.B SENTINELBOX_MAPPINGS
Path to the JSON file containing the mapping between syscalls and human-readable semantic feedback. Default: \fI./mappings/syscall_feedback.json\fR.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Run a simple shell snippet under the \fIstrict\fR profile (Network blocked):

.RS
.B sentinelbox --profile=strict --rootfs=./rootfs/busybox -- /bin/sh -c "echo Hello; nc -w1 example.com 80"
.RE

.PP
Run a Python data processing script, utilizing a custom rootfs and the relaxed \fIdatascience\fR profile:

.RS
.B sentinelbox --profile=datascience --rootfs=/srv/ml-rootfs -- python3 /work/train_model.py
.RE

.PP
Run the sandbox without the Rust monitor (pure kernel enforcement):

.RS
.B sentinelbox --no-monitor --rootfs=./rootfs/busybox -- /bin/sh
.RE

.SH BUGS AND LIMITATIONS
.TP
.B Docker / WSL2 Cgroup Delegation
When running SentinelBox inside a containerized environment (like Docker or WSL2) without explicit privileged configuration, Cgroup v2 delegation will likely fail, resulting in a \fBPermission denied\fR error when attempting to create the sandbox's resource group. 
.br
\fBWorkaround:\fR SentinelBox implements a graceful fallback mechanism. If it cannot read the sandboxed \fIcpu.stat\fR or \fImemory.current\fR, it will fallback to reporting global host metrics (via \fI/proc/stat\fR) to ensure the telemetry dashboard remains functional, though the hard resource caps will not be enforced. For strict resource enforcement, run SentinelBox on a native Linux host.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
The sandboxed program executed and exited normally with status 0.
.TP
.B 127
SentinelBox initialization failed (e.g., missing rootfs, failed to create namespaces) before the target could be executed.
.TP
.B 137
The sandboxed program was forcefully killed (SIGKILL). This is typically caused by triggering a syscall rule with the \fBKILL\fR action, or by the OOM (Out Of Memory) killer if Cgroup limits are exceeded.
.TP
.B Others
Any other exit status is the exact return code of the sandboxed command itself.

